  "name": "Vegan 'Fish' Patties in Tomato Sauce",
  "name_hebrew": "קציצות דג טבעוניות",
  "name_origin": "The name provided is modern descriptive Hebrew rather than a traditional Judeo-Arabic term, reflecting the dish's status as a contemporary adaptation. 'Ktzi'tzot' (patties) derives from the Hebrew root K-Tz-Tz (ק-צ-ץ), meaning 'to chop' or 'cut off.' The culinary inspiration, 'Chraime' (or Hraime), comes from the Arabic root 'ḥ-r-m' (forbidden/hot), specifically the diminutive form in Libyan and Tunisian Arabic meaning 'the little hot/spicy one,' referring to the piquant paprika and garlic sauce.",
  "description": "A clever vegan adaptation of the traditional North African fish dish. Tofu and wakame seaweed are used to replicate the texture and flavor of the sea, baked into patties and served in a classic spicy tomato and pepper sauce.",
  "cultural_context": "While tofu is not traditional to Djerban or Moroccan cuisine, this recipe adapts the classic 'Chraime' or 'Moroccan Fish' flavor profile (spicy tomato, garlic, cilantro) for a plant-based diet, maintaining the soul of the Friday night dinner.",
  "is_vegan": true,
  "vegan_adaptation_notes": "This recipe is inherently vegan, replacing white fish with extra firm tofu and using seaweed for flavor.",
